</table><para id="fs-idp27014944">In Table 1, Saudi Arabia has an absolute advantage in the production of oil because it only takes an hour to produce a barrel of oil compared to two hours in South Africa. South Africa has an absolute advantage in the production of maize.</para><para id="fs-idp7061664">To simplify, let’s say that Saudi Arabia and South Africa each have 100 worker hours (see Table 2). We illustrate what each country is capable of producing on its own using a <term class="no-emphasis">production possibility frontier (PPF)</term> graph, shown in Figure 1. Recall that the production possibilities frontier shows the maximum amount that each country can produce given its limited resources, in this case workers, and its level of technology.</para><table id="Table_33_02" summary="This table has three rows and four columns. The first row is a header row and it labels the columns, “Country”, “Oil Production using 100 worker hours (barrels)”, the third column is not labeled, and “Corn Production using 100 worker hours (bushels)”. Under the column “Country” are Saudi Arabia and the United States. Under the column “Oil Production using 100 worker hours (barrels)” are the values 100 and 50. Under the column that is not labeled are the words or and or. Under the column “Corn Production using 100 worker hours (bushels)” are the values 25 and 100."><title>Production Possibilities before Trade</title>
